    Direct replication attempt to evaluate a claim from Altmann_JournLabEco_2012_WLkV
Replication team: Miguel A. Fonseca
SCORE RR ID: 67516
OSF Project: https://osf.io/q7jk4
Instructions
For each claim that you are evaluating in this direct replication attempt, please complete all sections below. Please feel free to remove these and the other instructions for the final report that you provide on OSF.
Each claim evaluation must include a binary determination of whether or not the claim was replicated, given the inferential criteria. In other words, a sentence along the lines of “This claim [was/was not] replicated.” should appear in every claim evaluation. You can (and should!) also articulate in your discussion why this interpretation may be limited, but programmatic requirements of the SCORE project at large include the binary decision so it must be present.
There are also specific requirements for reporting the results of inferential tests:
Any p-value should be reported as an exact value, not a threshold, e.g.“p = .047” rather than “p < .05”. Please also indicate whether it is from a one- or two-tailed test.
Report the full text of your results with as much precision as possible. For example, a satisfactory report for the focal coefficient might be “unstandardized OLS coefficient for income term = 0.342367” vs an unsatisfactory report of “beta = 0.34”.
Please verify that for any test that was used as the basis for a power analysis, you are reporting the same effect size type used in that power analysis. It may not be the same type of effect size as was reported in the original paper (e.g., we convert to Cohen’s f squared to power many regression analyses, which is not commonly reported).
For any test that does not have a corresponding power analysis, please provide an effect size that corresponds to one from the original paper to the extent possible.
In the case of a regression analysis, please report the most unstandardized coefficient possible, e.g., the log-odds instead of the odds ratio. You may also report standardized values.
If there are multiple cells/conditions or levels to your analysis, please provide the sample sizes for each cell or level, e.g., “234823 participants nested within 32 countries” or “angry condition n = 83, happy condition n = 85”.
If multiple claims are evaluated using the same model, it is ok to group them together. In that case, please ensure that it is still clear which specific test/coefficient corresponds to which claim ID, and that there is still an evaluation of whether each claim replicated or not.
Scientific notation is acceptable for especially small or large values.
These requirements apply to all “simple” tests (one inferential test expected to be significant) and any inferential test contained within a “complex” test of a claim.
If applicable, please also distinguish which results come from an analysis of (a) entirely new data, (b) “hybrid” data (composed of both data that was used in the original study and new data), and/or (c) entirely original data.
Claim evaluation
Single-trace claim
Coded claim 4 text (original paper): Columns 1 and 2 of table 2 show that first-stage behavior differs considerably between the two treatments. Average effort in the first stage of the two-stage treatment is 84.8 (median = 84). Thus, subjects behave much more competitively in the multistage tournament, exerting efforts that are almost 20% higher than those of their counterparts in the one-stage treatment (average effort = 71.7, median = 75). A Mann-Whitney U-test confirms that the treatment difference is statistically significant (|z| = 2.536, p = .011, two sided).
Replication outcome: Simple test
Inferential criteria: The mean effort in the TS treatment is higher than in the OS treatment and the p-value from the Mann-Whitney test of their difference is less than 0.05.
Result: The mean effort in the TS treatment is lower than in the OS treatment, but the p-value from from the Mann-Whitney test of their difference is larger than 0.05 (p=0.150)
Deviations from the preregistration: Upon printing the materials to run the first session, I realized that I only uploaded the comprehension quiz for the TS treatment. The OS comprehension quiz used only Q1 from the uploaded questionnaire, and removed any mention of “second stage”.
Discussion: I had a server crash in the very first session (TS treatment), which meant we could not collect socio-demographic data for those participants. I recovered session data from the GSF file generated by z-tree. The format is different from that produced in normal sessions. 
Additional analyses (optional)
In the interest of comparing the two sets of results, and for the sake of clarity, I replicate the relevant section of Table 2 in Altmann, Falk and Wibral (2012), and I add alongside the new set of results.


General discussion (optional)
It is noticeable that in the OS treatment, the mean and median effort are noticeably lower than in the original study; in the TS treatment, both mean and median effort are lower in the original study than the replication. 
Description of materials provided
All materials on this OSF project may be shared publicly.
File description:
“1stage_ztree305_english.ztt”: zTree file used to run OS treatment
“2stage_ztree305_english.ztt”:zTree file used to run TS treatment
“Comprehension Quiz” comprehension quiz for TS treatment
“consent_form.ztt”: zTree file used to run consent form
“Cost Table.docx”: cost table 
“Instructions (OS).docx”: instructions for OS treatment
“Instructions (TS).docx”: instructions for TS treatment
“Questionnaire2015102000z4.ztq”: zTree file used to collect socio-demographic data
”Screenshots.zip”: file with zTree screenshots (for peer review purposes).
The data generated by zTree for each session was stored in two files: 
yymmdd_hhmm.csv
yymmdd_hhmm_sbj.csv
The files are stored in csv format for two reasons:
The file format used by zTree is not recognized by Stata
The .sbj file generated by “Questionnaire2015102000z4.ztq” contained payment information and I had to anonymize it prior to uploading. I manually anonymized each .sbj file by deleting rows recording email and payment preference; after doing so, I saved the file in .csv format and added _sbj to the name to distinguish it from the behavior data file. 
“data cleaning and analysis.do”: STATA .do file that cleans and runs the main analysis. 
The data for the session that suffered a crash is stored in “2059_subjects.csv”.
I stored all csv data files in a zip file (“raw_data.zip”) for ease of access.
“altmann_test.smcl” STATA log file with hypothesis test
“altmann_test.pdf” pdf copy of STATA log file with hypothesis test
“FinalData.csv” cleaned dataset used in analysis and to generate Table
I manually entered values for variable that indicated whether subjects proceed to stage 2 in observations for the crashed session. This is not relevant for the hypothesis test, simply to calculate Stage 2 effort (mean, median, min, max and SD).
“DataDictionary.csv” data dictionary
References
Altmann, S., Falk, A., & Wibral, M. (2012). Promotions and incentives: The case of multistage elimination tournaments. Journal of Labor Economics, 30(1), 149-174.

